## Measurements

### Temperature and Flow Rate Data

| Run | Configuration | Tc,in (°C) | Th,in (°C) | Tc,out (°C) | Th,out (°C) | Flow Rate (gal/hr) |
|-----|--------------|------------|------------|-------------|-------------|--------------------|
| 1 | Parallel flow | 6.8 | 40.0 | 15.9 | 24.6 | 210 |
| 2 | Parallel flow | 8.7 | 35.0 | 21.1 | 23.7 | 210 |
| 3 | Counterflow | 9.2 | 35.0 | 22.1 | 18.0 | 210 |
| 4 | Counterflow (hot start) | 10.0 | 40.0 | 23.9 | 19.6 | 210 |

![Measured temperatures](/assets/images/image-2.png)

---

### Heat Transfer Results

| Run | Configuration | ΔTc (K) | Qc (kW) | ΔTh (K) | Qh (kW) |
|-----|--------------|---------|---------|---------|---------|
| 1 | Parallel flow | 9.1 | 8.40 | 15.4 | 14.21 |
| 2 | Parallel flow | 12.4 | 11.44 | 11.3 | 10.43 |
| 3 | Counterflow | 12.9 | 11.91 | 17.0 | 15.69 |
| 4 | Counterflow (hot start) | 13.9 | 12.83 | 20.4 | 18.83 |

Based on cold-side measurements, the heat exchanger transferred approximately **8–13 kW** across all runs.

Differences between the hot- and cold-side heat transfer rates are expected due to heat loss to the surroundings, unequal flow rates, imperfect reservoir mixing, and sensor lag. These effects are typical in real experimental systems.

---

### Effectiveness

![Effectiveness comparison](/assets/images/image-3.png)

| Run | Configuration | Effectiveness (ε) |
|-----|--------------|------------------|
| 1 | Parallel flow | 0.27 |
| 2 | Parallel flow | 0.47 |
| 3 | Counterflow | 0.50 |
| 4 | Counterflow (hot start) | 0.46 |

For the most direct comparison between flow arrangements, Run 2 (parallel flow) and Run 3 (counterflow) were analyzed because they had nearly identical inlet temperatures. Under these matched conditions, the counterflow configuration achieved slightly higher effectiveness and heat transfer.

---

## Conclusions

This experiment demonstrated practical thermodynamic analysis of a working heat exchanger:

- Cold-side heat transfer rates ranged from **8 to 13 kW**  
- Counterflow achieved higher effectiveness (0.50) than parallel flow (0.47) under similar inlet conditions  
- Increasing the hot inlet temperature in counterflow increased heat transfer by approximately **8%**  
- Energy mismatches were expected due to real heat losses and flow nonuniformities  

Overall, this lab illustrated how both design choices (flow arrangement) and operating conditions (inlet temperature) directly affect heat exchanger performance.

